    "8308276": {
      "title": "Depth-first search is inherently sequential",
      "abstract": "Abstract This paper concerns the computational complexity of depth-first search. Suppose we are given a rooted graph G with fixed adjacency lists and vertices u, v. We wish to test if u is first visited before v in depth-first search order of G. We show that this problem, for undirected and directed graphs, is complete in deterministic polynomial time with respect to deterministic log-space reductions. This gives strong evidence that depth-first search ordering can be done neither in deterministic space (log n) c nor in parallel time (log n) c , for any constant c > 0."
